User Guide
Step 1: Power Connections

Connect all components using the breadboard.

Connect positive (VCC) and negative (GND) of the servo motors to the power rails of the breadboard.
Connect the breadboard power rails to the power bank (5V and GND).
Also power the ESP32 using the same power bank (via USB or Vin & GND).
Step 2: Servo Signal Connections
Connect the signal wire of the hopper servo motor to GPIO pin 12 of the ESP32.
Connect the signal wire of the slide servo motor to GPIO pin 13.
Ensure all grounds are common.
Step 3: Configure Wi-Fi in ESP32 Code

Open the ESP32 code and update:

Wi-Fi Name (SSID)
Wi-Fi Password
Upload the code to the ESP32 using Arduino IDE.
Step 4: Set IP Address in Laptop Code

After uploading the code:

Open the Serial Monitor and note the IP address displayed by the ESP32.
Update this IP address in your laptop (Python) program.
Step 5: Connect Webcam and Run Program
Connect the webcam to the laptop.
Run the Python/OpenCV program.
Step 6: Set Hopper Position

Ensure the hopper servo is at 90° (Detect Position).
This is necessary for proper alignment of the ball in front of the camera.

Step 7: Calibrate Slide Servo
Show a pink ball to the camera.
Observe where the slide servo moves.
If incorrect:
Remove the servo horn (arm)
Adjust it manually
Reattach it so it points to the correct container for pink
Step 8: Run the System

Run the program in the VS Code terminal.

If it shows “Connected through Wi-Fi”, the system is working properly.
If not, restart the laptop program and try again.
